  &lt;p id="Qlb9bM"&gt;In addition to launching two &lt;a href="https://www.theverge.com/e/22381247"&gt;new&lt;/a&gt; foldable &lt;a href="https://www.theverge.com/e/22381267"&gt;phones&lt;/a&gt; and a pair of &lt;a href="https://www.theverge.com/e/22382573"&gt;smartwatches&lt;/a&gt;, Samsung today announced its latest set of wireless earbuds. The Galaxy Buds 2 cost $149.99 and will replace the Galaxy Buds Plus in the company’s lineup. (It’s still possible to find remaining stock of the Buds Plus at some retailers, but they’ll be gone once that inventory runs dry.) Preorders start today in a range of colors that include dark gray, white, purple, and green, and the Buds 2 will be available on August 27th. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p id="4wIFP0"&gt;They’ve got a design that’s similar to the more expensive &lt;a href="https://www.theverge.com/2021/1/15/22231848/samsung-galaxy-buds-pro-review"&gt;Galaxy Buds Pro&lt;/a&gt;, only smaller. In fact, Samsung says these are the smallest and lightest true wireless earbuds it has made yet. Also like the Buds Pro, the Buds 2 have two-way drivers...&lt;/p&gt;
